Money Stuff =0A The basic theory of bank regulation is that, left to their =
own devices, =0Abankers would make banks too risky, so regulators and super=
visors ar =0A=0A=0A <> =0A =0A<https://sli.bloomberg.com/click=3Fs=3D825881=
&stpe=3Ddefault&li=3D11758815&m=3D21d6dea82d6b16615cf44233be620525&p=3D1119=
2024>=0A=0A=0A=0AFed insider trading=0A=0AThe basic theory of bank regulati=
on is that, left to their own devices, =0Abankers would make banks too risk=
y, so regulators and supervisors are there to =0Amake banks more boring. A =
bank is, roughly, a big pot of assets bought with =0Adepositors=E2=80=99 mo=
ney; the bank owns essentially anoption on those assets. If the =0Aassets g=
o up, the bank gets a highly leveraged return; if the assets go down, =0Ath=
e losses are largely the depositors=E2=80=99 (or the taxpayers=E2=80=99) pr=
oblem. =E2=80=9CHeads I =0Awin, tails you lose,=E2=80=9D etc., you know all=
 this stuff.=0A=0AAnd so banks have incentives to buy high-risk, high-retur=
n assets with as much =0Aleverage as possible, and risk-based capital regul=
ation and prudential bank =0Asupervision counteract those incentives. The b=
ankers =E2=80=94 who own stock in their =0Abanks and get paid bonuses for m=
aking money =E2=80=94 push for more risk and more =0Avolatility, and the ba=
